Good morning, can you hear me? I think that you can hear me because I cannot see any problem. The microphone is okay and the video is okay. So let me first share my document and after that we continue our course this week.

2
00:00:35,039 --> 00:01:11,790
Yes, software matrix. This is the week number five, as I remember. Yes, absolutely. It will take a few seconds and after that we can make our course.

3
00:01:11,790 --> 00:01:54,530
I'm asking again, is there any problem? Can you hear me? Depending on the speed of the internet, the upload process will take a few seconds.

4
00:01:54,530 --> 00:02:28,680
We need to be patient. So let me arrange the position. Yes, the title will be the geometry of software measurements.

5
00:02:28,680 --> 00:03:03,080
The geometry of software measurements. But the uploading process is going on at that moment. I think it's okay.

6
00:03:03,080 --> 00:03:09,360
The geometry of software measurements.

7
00:03:09,360 --> 00:03:11,379
Today,

8
00:03:11,379 --> 00:03:19,240
we begin with the idea of geometry of software measurement.

9
00:03:19,240 --> 00:03:30,680
This title is interesting because it suggests that software measurement is not random.

10
00:03:30,680 --> 00:03:42,150
It's not random. It has structure. It has dimensions. It has relationships.

11
00:03:42,150 --> 00:03:45,150
Just like geometry studies,

12
00:03:45,150 --> 00:03:46,150
shapes,

13
00:03:46,150 --> 00:03:50,169
and dimensions.

14
00:03:50,169 --> 00:04:06,840
Just like it, software measurement studies different aspects of development in an organized way.

15
00:04:06,840 --> 00:04:21,389
The subtitle at the bottom of the main title gives the core idea, a goal-based framework for classifying,

16
00:04:21,389 --> 00:04:24,519
process,

17
00:04:24,519 --> 00:04:25,519
products,

18
00:04:25,519 --> 00:04:28,800
and resources.

19
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:31,660
These three elements,

20
00:04:31,660 --> 00:04:32,660
process,

21
00:04:32,660 --> 00:04:34,660
products,

22
00:04:34,660 --> 00:04:37,079
and resource,

23
00:04:37,079 --> 00:04:45,550
form the foundation of how we measure software systems.

24
00:04:45,550 --> 00:04:50,189
Let's start with process first.

25
00:04:50,189 --> 00:04:56,879
A process represents activities over time.

26
00:04:56,879 --> 00:05:12,360
It includes development steps like requirements analysis, design, coding, testing, or maintenance.

27
00:05:12,360 --> 00:05:25,519
In measurement terms, we often look at duration, effort, cost, or number of defects found during a process.

28
00:05:25,519 --> 00:05:27,519
Processes are dynamic.

29
00:05:27,519 --> 00:05:39,319
They involve workflow transformation and input turning into output.

30
00:05:39,319 --> 00:05:44,839
Next, we have product.

31
00:05:44,839 --> 00:05:52,680
A product is any artifact produced during the software lifecycle.

32
00:05:52,680 --> 00:05:57,370
It can be source code,

33
00:05:57,370 --> 00:06:00,139
design diagrams,

34
00:06:00,139 --> 00:06:04,519
test cases,

35
00:06:04,519 --> 00:06:07,250
documentation,

36
00:06:07,250 --> 00:06:10,250
or the final software system.

37
00:06:10,250 --> 00:06:19,870
Products can be measured using attributes like size,

38
00:06:19,870 --> 00:06:21,870
complexity,

39
00:06:21,870 --> 00:06:23,899
modularity,

40
00:06:23,899 --> 00:06:25,930
reliability,

41
00:06:25,930 --> 00:06:27,930
or maintainability.

42
00:06:27,930 --> 00:06:34,050
Some of these are internal attributes,

43
00:06:34,050 --> 00:06:39,519
like lines of code.

44
00:06:39,519 --> 00:06:40,519
Others are external,

45
00:06:40,519 --> 00:06:43,519
or external attributes,

46
00:06:43,519 --> 00:06:50,350
like usability or performance.

47
00:06:50,350 --> 00:06:56,120
And finally, we consider resources.

48
00:06:56,120 --> 00:07:06,250
Resources include people.

49
00:07:06,250 --> 00:07:08,250
Resources, yes,

50
00:07:08,250 --> 00:07:12,250
include people and tools,

51
00:07:12,250 --> 00:07:15,339
hardware,

52
00:07:15,339 --> 00:07:16,339
methods,

53
00:07:16,339 --> 00:07:20,959
and teams.

54
00:07:20,959 --> 00:07:24,959
These are the inputs used to produce software.

55
00:07:24,959 --> 00:07:32,490
We measure resources in terms of costs.

56
00:07:32,490 --> 00:07:34,490
In terms of costs,

57
00:07:34,490 --> 00:07:36,490
experience level,

58
00:07:36,490 --> 00:07:39,129
productivity,

59
00:07:39,129 --> 00:07:42,160
or skill utilization.

60
00:07:42,160 --> 00:07:46,639
If we give an example,

61
00:07:46,639 --> 00:07:56,329
productivity is often calculated as output divided by effort.

62
00:07:56,329 --> 00:08:03,329
It connects product measurements with process measurements.

63
00:08:03,329 --> 00:08:10,410
What is powerful here is the goal-based idea.

64
00:08:10,410 --> 00:08:15,759
We do not measure everything.

65
00:08:15,759 --> 00:08:19,759
We measure what supports our goals.

66
00:08:19,759 --> 00:08:28,439
If our goal is improving reliability,

67
00:08:28,439 --> 00:08:32,110
we select metrics

68
00:08:32,110 --> 00:08:35,110
that relate to faults,

69
00:08:35,110 --> 00:08:36,110
failures,

70
00:08:36,110 --> 00:08:38,110
and defect detection.

71
00:08:38,110 --> 00:08:49,029
If our goal is improving productivity,

72
00:08:49,029 --> 00:08:55,029
we focus on effort and output ratios.

73
00:08:55,029 --> 00:09:00,549
So,

74
00:09:00,549 --> 00:09:03,549
instead of measuring randomly,

75
00:09:03,549 --> 00:09:08,350
this framework gives us structure.

76
00:09:08,350 --> 00:09:14,200
It tells us to first

77
00:09:14,200 --> 00:09:18,200
classify what we are measuring

78
00:09:18,200 --> 00:09:20,840
or process,

79
00:09:20,840 --> 00:09:21,840
product,

80
00:09:21,840 --> 00:09:22,840
or resources.

81
00:09:22,840 --> 00:09:25,090
And then

82
00:09:25,090 --> 00:09:28,090
define metrics

83
00:09:28,090 --> 00:09:31,090
that align with our goals.

84
00:09:31,090 --> 00:09:38,000
This geometric perspective

85
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:41,000
helps us think in dimensions.

86
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:44,700
Every measurement belongs somewhere

87
00:09:44,700 --> 00:09:47,700
in the structured space.

88
00:09:47,700 --> 00:09:52,519
And understanding

89
00:09:52,519 --> 00:09:55,059
that structure

90
00:09:55,059 --> 00:09:58,059
is the first step towards meaningful

91
00:09:58,059 --> 00:10:13,309
and valid software measurements.

92
00:10:13,309 --> 00:10:17,980
Now we move to a very important principle.

93
00:10:17,980 --> 00:10:20,980
Measurement requires classification.

94
00:10:20,980 --> 00:10:29,200
We often say we want quality.

95
00:10:29,200 --> 00:10:32,649
We want better software.

96
00:10:32,649 --> 00:10:35,419
Fewer bugs.

97
00:10:35,419 --> 00:10:38,090
Higher reliability.

98
00:10:38,090 --> 00:10:42,820
Lower costs.

99
00:10:42,820 --> 00:10:46,820
But the word quality is abstract.

100
00:10:46,820 --> 00:10:50,610
It's vojo.

101
00:10:50,610 --> 00:10:54,610
If we do not define it properly,

102
00:10:54,610 --> 00:10:58,320
we cannot measure it.

103
00:10:58,320 --> 00:11:04,120
It needs to be defined properly.

104
00:11:04,120 --> 00:11:12,330
And if it cannot be defined properly,

105
00:11:12,330 --> 00:11:14,330
we cannot measure it.

106
00:11:14,330 --> 00:11:18,330
And if we cannot measure it,

107
00:11:18,330 --> 00:11:21,330
we cannot control it.

108
00:11:21,330 --> 00:11:23,480
So,

109
00:11:23,480 --> 00:11:26,480
this slide introduces

110
00:11:26,480 --> 00:11:30,480
a key measurement rule.

111
00:11:30,480 --> 00:11:34,960
You cannot set a meaningful goal

112
00:11:34,960 --> 00:11:37,960
until you identify two things.

113
00:11:37,960 --> 00:11:43,190
The entity

114
00:11:43,190 --> 00:11:46,190
and the attributes.

115
00:11:46,190 --> 00:11:48,279
First,

116
00:11:48,279 --> 00:11:49,279
the entity.

117
00:11:49,279 --> 00:11:51,279
Let's study the entity.

118
00:11:51,279 --> 00:11:54,789
What is entity?

119
00:11:54,789 --> 00:11:57,200
The entity is the thing

120
00:11:57,200 --> 00:12:00,720
we are measuring.

121
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:03,720
It could be a process

122
00:12:03,720 --> 00:12:04,720
like testing,

123
00:12:04,720 --> 00:12:05,720
for example.

124
00:12:05,720 --> 00:12:09,259
Or it could be a product

125
00:12:09,259 --> 00:12:12,409
like source code.

126
00:12:12,409 --> 00:12:15,409
Or it could be a resource

127
00:12:15,409 --> 00:12:21,259
like a development team.

128
00:12:21,259 --> 00:12:22,259
Second,

129
00:12:22,259 --> 00:12:23,259
the attributes.

130
00:12:23,259 --> 00:12:25,259
What is attributes?

131
00:12:25,259 --> 00:12:30,159
The attribute is the property

132
00:12:30,159 --> 00:12:33,399
of that entity.

133
00:12:33,399 --> 00:12:35,399
If we do an example,

134
00:12:35,399 --> 00:12:38,399
if the entity is code,

135
00:12:38,399 --> 00:12:43,110
the attribute could be the size

136
00:12:43,110 --> 00:12:45,110
or complexity

137
00:12:45,110 --> 00:12:47,110
and reliability

138
00:12:47,110 --> 00:12:50,769
or maintainability.

139
00:12:50,769 --> 00:12:54,769
If the entity is a testing process,

140
00:12:54,769 --> 00:12:58,159
so the attributes

141
00:12:58,159 --> 00:13:01,159
could be cost

142
00:13:01,159 --> 00:13:02,159
or duration

143
00:13:02,159 --> 00:13:04,159
or effectiveness.

144
00:13:04,159 --> 00:13:09,720
Without clearly separating

145
00:13:09,720 --> 00:13:12,720
entity and attributes,

146
00:13:12,720 --> 00:13:15,720
we mix concepts.

147
00:13:15,720 --> 00:13:20,059
For example,

148
00:13:20,059 --> 00:13:26,139
saying we want better quality.

149
00:13:26,139 --> 00:13:28,809
It is not enough.

150
00:13:28,809 --> 00:13:31,809
Saying that is not enough.

151
00:13:31,809 --> 00:13:33,809
Better quality of what?

152
00:13:33,809 --> 00:13:35,580
Code.

153
00:13:35,580 --> 00:13:36,580
You mean code?

154
00:13:36,580 --> 00:13:38,580
You mean design

155
00:13:38,580 --> 00:13:40,580
or testing process?

156
00:13:40,580 --> 00:13:43,580
And which aspects?

157
00:13:43,580 --> 00:13:45,580
Reliability?

158
00:13:45,580 --> 00:13:48,120
Usability?

159
00:13:48,120 --> 00:13:50,120
Or cost effectiveness?

160
00:13:50,120 --> 00:13:51,120
What do you mean?

161
00:13:51,120 --> 00:13:56,600
The image in the slides

162
00:13:56,600 --> 00:13:59,490
in the center

163
00:13:59,490 --> 00:14:02,679
acts like a classification.

164
00:14:02,679 --> 00:14:06,899
A classification filter.

165
00:14:06,899 --> 00:14:07,899
Many terms

166
00:14:07,899 --> 00:14:09,899
such as cost,

167
00:14:09,899 --> 00:14:12,320
speed,

168
00:14:12,320 --> 00:14:14,860
comfort,

169
00:14:14,860 --> 00:14:15,860
reliability,

170
00:14:15,860 --> 00:14:16,860
maintainability

171
00:14:16,860 --> 00:14:17,860
and bugs

172
00:14:17,860 --> 00:14:20,860
are flowing into the system.

173
00:14:20,860 --> 00:14:26,440
But before measuring,

174
00:14:26,440 --> 00:14:28,440
we must filter them.

175
00:14:28,440 --> 00:14:32,460
So,

176
00:14:32,460 --> 00:14:40,960
before the measuring process,

177
00:14:40,960 --> 00:14:45,960
we must use the filtering process.

178
00:14:45,960 --> 00:14:49,440
We must organize them

179
00:14:49,440 --> 00:14:55,840
into a structured measurement framework.

180
00:14:55,840 --> 00:14:57,840
This is where classification

181
00:14:57,840 --> 00:15:00,259
becomes essential.

182
00:15:00,259 --> 00:15:04,259
It moves us from emotional goals

183
00:15:04,259 --> 00:15:07,259
to concrete geometry.

184
00:15:07,259 --> 00:15:08,259
Instead of saying

185
00:15:08,259 --> 00:15:10,259
we want fewer bugs,

186
00:15:10,259 --> 00:15:13,259
we define entity

187
00:15:13,259 --> 00:15:15,259
the software products

188
00:15:15,259 --> 00:15:19,549
attributes number of defects

189
00:15:19,549 --> 00:15:25,000
per kilo.

190
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:27,000
Now the goal

191
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:32,370
becomes measurable.

192
00:15:32,370 --> 00:15:34,370
So, the main idea

193
00:15:34,370 --> 00:15:37,299
is discipline.

194
00:15:37,299 --> 00:15:39,299
Measurement is not about

195
00:15:39,299 --> 00:15:41,299
collecting numbers randomly.

196
00:15:41,299 --> 00:15:45,299
It is about defining clearly

197
00:15:45,299 --> 00:15:47,299
what is the entity,

198
00:15:47,299 --> 00:15:50,679
what is the attribute.

199
00:15:50,679 --> 00:15:54,320
Only after that

200
00:15:54,320 --> 00:15:58,320
can we select proper metrics

201
00:15:58,320 --> 00:16:01,320
and set meaningful goals.

202
00:16:01,320 --> 00:16:10,960
Yes.

203
00:16:10,960 --> 00:16:17,649
The three software entities.

204
00:16:17,649 --> 00:16:22,669
Now we focus

205
00:16:22,669 --> 00:16:24,830
on the core structure

206
00:16:24,830 --> 00:16:27,830
of software measurements.

207
00:16:27,830 --> 00:16:32,269
The three software entities.

208
00:16:32,269 --> 00:16:37,789
Everything in this framework

209
00:16:37,789 --> 00:16:39,789
revolves around

210
00:16:39,789 --> 00:16:43,460
three fundamental elements.

211
00:16:43,460 --> 00:16:44,460
Resources,

212
00:16:44,460 --> 00:16:45,460
processes

213
00:16:45,460 --> 00:16:47,460
and products.

214
00:16:47,460 --> 00:16:55,590
These are not random categories.

215
00:16:55,590 --> 00:16:56,590
They represent

216
00:16:56,590 --> 00:16:58,590
the full lifecycle

217
00:16:58,590 --> 00:17:00,590
of software development

218
00:17:00,590 --> 00:17:05,920
in a silical model.

219
00:17:05,920 --> 00:17:07,920
Let's start with resources.

220
00:17:07,920 --> 00:17:09,920
It is input.

221
00:17:09,920 --> 00:17:14,200
Resources are the entities

222
00:17:14,200 --> 00:17:17,200
required to perform an activity.

223
00:17:17,200 --> 00:17:21,289
These include people,

224
00:17:21,289 --> 00:17:23,900
teams,

225
00:17:23,900 --> 00:17:26,920
tools,

226
00:17:26,920 --> 00:17:29,500
hardware,

227
00:17:29,500 --> 00:17:31,500
software platforms

228
00:17:31,500 --> 00:17:33,559
and methods.

229
00:17:33,559 --> 00:17:35,759
Without resources

230
00:17:35,759 --> 00:17:37,759
nothing happens.

231
00:17:37,759 --> 00:17:40,299
They are the inputs

232
00:17:40,299 --> 00:17:42,299
of the

233
00:17:42,299 --> 00:17:44,299
the input size

234
00:17:44,299 --> 00:17:47,289
of the system.

235
00:17:47,289 --> 00:17:50,289
When we measure resources

236
00:17:50,289 --> 00:17:53,799
we might look at costs.

237
00:17:53,799 --> 00:17:57,210
Also we might look at

238
00:17:57,210 --> 00:17:59,210
experience level

239
00:17:59,210 --> 00:18:01,210
and team size.

240
00:18:01,210 --> 00:18:04,529
Scale distribution

241
00:18:04,529 --> 00:18:06,529
or tool capability.

242
00:18:06,529 --> 00:18:10,609
Next,

243
00:18:10,609 --> 00:18:15,000
we move to process activity.

244
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:29,619
Processes are software related activities

245
00:18:29,619 --> 00:18:32,720
that occur over time.

246
00:18:32,720 --> 00:18:35,579
Designing,

247
00:18:35,579 --> 00:18:37,579
coding,

248
00:18:37,579 --> 00:18:38,579
testing,

249
00:18:38,579 --> 00:18:40,579
maintaining.

250
00:18:40,579 --> 00:18:44,160
These are all processes.

251
00:18:44,160 --> 00:18:46,160
They transform

252
00:18:46,160 --> 00:18:48,160
inputs

253
00:18:48,160 --> 00:18:51,789
into outputs.

254
00:18:51,789 --> 00:18:54,880
Processes have duration,

255
00:18:54,880 --> 00:18:56,880
efforts,

256
00:18:56,880 --> 00:18:57,880
sequence

257
00:18:57,880 --> 00:19:00,839
and structure.

258
00:19:00,839 --> 00:19:03,839
When measuring processes

259
00:19:03,839 --> 00:19:07,480
we focus on time,

260
00:19:07,480 --> 00:19:10,480
we focus on costs,

261
00:19:10,480 --> 00:19:12,480
we focus on number of

262
00:19:12,480 --> 00:19:14,480
defects found

263
00:19:14,480 --> 00:19:17,480
and also efficiency

264
00:19:17,480 --> 00:19:19,480
and we focus on

265
00:19:19,480 --> 00:19:23,539
cost effectiveness.

266
00:19:23,539 --> 00:19:25,539
Then we arrive at

267
00:19:25,539 --> 00:19:26,539
products,

268
00:19:26,539 --> 00:19:36,000
means outputs.

269
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:39,000
Products are the artifacts

270
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:41,000
and deliverables

271
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:44,000
produced by processes.

272
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:46,539
These include

273
00:19:46,539 --> 00:19:50,920
design documents,

274
00:19:50,920 --> 00:19:52,920
include also

275
00:19:52,920 --> 00:19:54,920
source code,

276
00:19:54,920 --> 00:19:56,980
classifications,

277
00:19:56,980 --> 00:19:57,980
test cases

278
00:19:57,980 --> 00:19:58,980
and

279
00:19:58,980 --> 00:20:02,900
the final system.

280
00:20:02,900 --> 00:20:03,900
Products are often

281
00:20:03,900 --> 00:20:06,900
easier to examine directly.

282
00:20:06,900 --> 00:20:09,900
We can measure size,

283
00:20:09,900 --> 00:20:12,900
complexity,

284
00:20:12,900 --> 00:20:15,509
modularity,

285
00:20:15,509 --> 00:20:16,509
coupling,

286
00:20:16,509 --> 00:20:18,509
reliability

287
00:20:18,509 --> 00:20:22,430
or maintainability.

288
00:20:22,430 --> 00:20:27,430
What makes this model powerful

289
00:20:27,430 --> 00:20:30,430
is its

290
00:20:30,430 --> 00:20:32,430
silent nature.

291
00:20:32,430 --> 00:20:37,250
Resources enable processes.

292
00:20:37,250 --> 00:20:40,250
Processes generate products.

293
00:20:40,250 --> 00:20:42,319
Products may require

294
00:20:42,319 --> 00:20:44,319
new processes for

295
00:20:44,319 --> 00:20:46,319
maintenance or evolution.

296
00:20:46,319 --> 00:20:48,829
And updated products

297
00:20:48,829 --> 00:20:50,829
may require

298
00:20:50,829 --> 00:20:52,829
new or improved

299
00:20:52,829 --> 00:20:54,829
resources.

300
00:20:54,829 --> 00:20:57,150
This means

301
00:20:57,150 --> 00:20:59,150
measurement cannot focus

302
00:20:59,150 --> 00:21:02,150
on only one dimension.

