Now, we focus on the first entity.

739
00:35:48,599 --> 00:35:50,599
The first entity in our framework.

740
00:35:50,599 --> 00:35:52,880
Processes.

741
00:35:52,880 --> 00:35:58,650
A process refers to software-related activities.

742
00:35:58,650 --> 00:36:13,400
These activities include requirements, engineering, detailed design, coding, integration, testing,

743
00:36:13,400 --> 00:36:20,679
and maintenance.

744
00:36:20,679 --> 00:36:21,679
Yes.

745
00:36:21,679 --> 00:36:23,829
Maintenance.

746
00:36:23,829 --> 00:36:30,889
One key characteristic of process is that they have duration.

747
00:36:30,889 --> 00:36:35,400
They happen over time.

748
00:36:35,400 --> 00:36:37,400
There is a clear start.

749
00:36:37,400 --> 00:36:39,400
There is execution.

750
00:36:39,400 --> 00:36:41,400
And there is completion.

751
00:36:41,400 --> 00:36:49,210
Because processes unfold over time.

752
00:36:49,210 --> 00:36:56,239
The measurement approach must capture that temporal dimension.

753
00:36:56,239 --> 00:37:02,239
The slide highlights three key metrics for processes.

754
00:37:02,239 --> 00:37:06,119
Duration.

755
00:37:06,119 --> 00:37:10,170
How long.

756
00:37:10,170 --> 00:37:11,300
Yes.

757
00:37:11,300 --> 00:37:18,179
How long does the process take?

758
00:37:18,179 --> 00:37:21,909
And effort.

759
00:37:21,909 --> 00:37:23,840
Cost.

760
00:37:23,840 --> 00:37:28,840
How much personal cost or human effort is involved?

761
00:37:28,840 --> 00:37:33,559
And incident count.

762
00:37:33,559 --> 00:37:39,849
Incident count.

763
00:37:39,849 --> 00:37:48,980
How many errors, effects, or significant events occur during the process?

764
00:37:48,980 --> 00:37:53,800
Let's break these down.

765
00:37:53,800 --> 00:38:01,500
Duration measures the total time from start to completion.

766
00:38:01,500 --> 00:38:07,500
For example, how many days does integration take?

767
00:38:07,500 --> 00:38:20,349
Duration helps us evaluate scheduling efficiency and planning accuracy.

768
00:38:20,349 --> 00:38:24,349
Effort usually refers to personal costs.

769
00:38:24,349 --> 00:38:33,630
It's often measured in person with person hours or person months.

770
00:38:33,630 --> 00:38:41,320
Effort tells us how many resources were consumed during the activity.

771
00:38:41,320 --> 00:38:48,869
A short duration with very high effort might indicate parallel staffing.

772
00:38:48,869 --> 00:39:07,440
A long duration with low effort might indicate inefficiency or delays.

773
00:39:07,440 --> 00:39:08,440
Yes.

774
00:39:08,440 --> 00:39:10,690
The incident count.

775
00:39:10,690 --> 00:39:16,690
Incident count represents measurable events during the process.

776
00:39:16,690 --> 00:39:20,110
These could be requirements, changes.

777
00:39:20,110 --> 00:39:21,110
Defects.

778
00:39:21,110 --> 00:39:26,840
Disforced.

779
00:39:26,840 --> 00:39:32,570
Integration failures or review findings.

780
00:39:32,570 --> 00:39:41,849
Incident counts could be requirements, requirement changes.

781
00:39:41,849 --> 00:39:52,039
Defects discovered and failures of integration or review findings.

782
00:39:52,039 --> 00:39:54,039
Incident metrics help evaluate processes.

783
00:39:54,039 --> 00:40:16,329
For example, if many defects are found during formal inspection, that may indicate strong detection capability.

784
00:40:16,329 --> 00:40:26,619
If many defects are found later in production, that may indicate weaknesses in earlier phase.

785
00:40:26,619 --> 00:40:33,119
Notice how these metrics are interconnected.

786
00:40:33,119 --> 00:40:39,380
Duration and effort combine to describe costs.

787
00:40:39,380 --> 00:40:49,530
Incident counts help us evaluate effectiveness and quality control within the process.

788
00:40:49,530 --> 00:40:56,599
Processes are dynamic entities.

789
00:40:56,599 --> 00:41:00,599
They transform resources into products.

790
00:41:00,599 --> 00:41:05,820
When measuring processes, we are not measuring structure.

791
00:41:05,820 --> 00:41:08,820
We are measuring performance over time.

792
00:41:08,820 --> 00:41:24,000
So, when defining a goal related to process improvements, we must ask, do we want to reduce duration?

793
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:28,869
Do we want to optimize efforts?

794
00:41:28,869 --> 00:41:32,480
Do we want to decrease late stage incidents?

795
00:41:32,480 --> 00:41:41,139
Clear goals lead to meaningful process metrics.

796
00:41:41,139 --> 00:42:02,599
Measuring process effectiveness.

797
00:42:02,599 --> 00:42:18,659
Now, we move deeper into process analysis with measuring process effectiveness.

798
00:42:18,659 --> 00:42:30,179
When we talk about effectiveness, we are asking a simple,

799
00:42:30,179 --> 00:42:33,690
but powerful question.

800
00:42:33,690 --> 00:42:47,889
Are we getting good results compared to what we invest?

801
00:42:47,889 --> 00:43:01,159
On the left side, we see the inputs, typically expressed as total costs or efforts.

802
00:43:01,159 --> 00:43:14,480
And on the right side, we see the outputs, often expressed as measurable results,

803
00:43:14,480 --> 00:43:24,300
such as errors per kilo or total number of detected defects.

804
00:43:24,300 --> 00:43:32,639
Between them, we evaluate an efficiency index.

805
00:43:32,639 --> 00:43:36,639
Look at two important derivative metrics.

806
00:43:36,639 --> 00:43:47,500
First, cost per error equals to total cost division number of errors.

807
00:43:47,500 --> 00:43:50,230
Cost per error equals to total cost division number of errors.

808
00:43:50,230 --> 00:43:59,539
Cost per error equals to total cost division number of errors.

809
00:43:59,539 --> 00:44:11,400
This metric tells us how much we are spending to detect or correct each defect.

810
00:44:11,400 --> 00:44:20,250
If cost per error is very high, the process may be inefficient.

811
00:44:20,250 --> 00:44:24,369
If it is low, the process may be cost-free.

812
00:44:24,369 --> 00:44:27,820
If it is low, the process may be cost-effective.

813
00:44:27,820 --> 00:44:35,340
But we must also consider quality.

814
00:44:35,340 --> 00:44:46,489
Second, inspection efficiency is equal to effort expanded division clock reuse.

815
00:44:46,489 --> 00:44:53,489
And this measure relates effort to the size of the product inspected.

816
00:44:53,489 --> 00:44:58,489
It gives us insight into productivity

817
00:44:58,489 --> 00:45:01,489
during inspection activities.

818
00:45:01,489 --> 00:45:10,590
For example, how many person-hours are needed to review 1,000 lines of code.

819
00:45:10,590 --> 00:45:22,219
Yes, how many person-hours are needed to review 1,000 lines of code.

820
00:45:22,219 --> 00:45:30,039
These metrics combine process and product measurements.

821
00:45:30,039 --> 00:45:33,039
Effort is a process attribute.

822
00:45:33,039 --> 00:45:36,679
Clock is a product attribute.

823
00:45:36,679 --> 00:45:39,969
Errors are incident counts.

824
00:45:39,969 --> 00:45:57,880
When we combine them, we obtain indirect measures that help managers make decisions.

825
00:45:57,880 --> 00:46:10,210
Managers often use these internal process statistics to judge broader external attributes,

826
00:46:10,210 --> 00:46:17,849
like stability, controllability, and quality.

827
00:46:17,849 --> 00:46:38,610
For instance, if inspection efficiency improves while error detection remains strong,

828
00:46:38,610 --> 00:46:44,380
that may indicate process improvements.

829
00:46:44,380 --> 00:46:56,909
However, effectiveness is not just about minimizing costs.

830
00:46:56,909 --> 00:47:11,840
A process that is cheap but fails to detect defects early,

831
00:47:11,840 --> 00:47:16,840
it may lead to much higher downstream costs.

832
00:47:16,840 --> 00:47:23,309
So, effectiveness always involves balance.

833
00:47:23,309 --> 00:47:30,880
The key idea here is comparison between inputs.

834
00:47:30,880 --> 00:47:34,510
And outputs.

835
00:47:34,510 --> 00:47:37,510
What goes into the process?

836
00:47:37,510 --> 00:47:41,510
And what comes out of the process?

837
00:47:41,510 --> 00:47:50,760
And what is the relationship between them?

838
00:47:50,760 --> 00:47:54,760
That relationship defines process effectiveness.

839
00:47:54,760 --> 00:48:32,090
Now we turn to the second measured entity in our framework.

840
00:48:32,090 --> 00:48:42,389
It's products.

841
00:48:42,389 --> 00:48:44,389
A product is defined as

842
00:48:44,389 --> 00:48:52,219
many artifacts or documents resulting from a process activity.

843
00:48:52,219 --> 00:48:56,340
This is very important.

844
00:48:56,340 --> 00:48:58,340
When we say products,

845
00:48:58,340 --> 00:49:11,280
we are not only talking about the final software.

846
00:49:11,280 --> 00:49:20,280
We are not only talking about the final software delivered to customers.

847
00:49:20,280 --> 00:49:22,440
We are talking about

848
00:49:23,510 --> 00:49:27,510
every artifact created during development.

849
00:49:27,510 --> 00:49:32,159
For example,

850
00:49:32,159 --> 00:49:37,510
requirements documents,

851
00:49:37,510 --> 00:49:40,510
design diagrams,

852
00:49:40,510 --> 00:49:43,949
source code,

853
00:49:43,949 --> 00:49:46,949
they are written in the slide,

854
00:49:46,949 --> 00:49:49,909
documentation,

855
00:49:49,909 --> 00:49:51,909
and test data.

856
00:49:51,909 --> 00:50:02,630
All of these are products.

857
00:50:02,630 --> 00:50:05,630
This means measurement does not apply only

858
00:50:05,630 --> 00:50:09,630
to the final executable system.

859
00:50:09,630 --> 00:50:16,239
It applies at every stage of the lifecycle.

860
00:50:16,239 --> 00:50:23,110
Requirements can be measured.

861
00:50:23,110 --> 00:50:26,239
Designs can be measured.

862
00:50:26,239 --> 00:50:32,239
Even test data and documentation can be measured.

863
00:50:32,239 --> 00:50:37,449
Let's consider some examples.

864
00:50:37,449 --> 00:50:39,449
For requirements,

865
00:50:39,449 --> 00:50:43,449
we must or we might measure size,

866
00:50:43,449 --> 00:50:45,449
clarity,

867
00:50:45,449 --> 00:50:47,480
redundancy,

868
00:50:47,480 --> 00:50:50,480
or number of requirement changes.

869
00:50:50,480 --> 00:50:53,380
For designs,

870
00:50:53,380 --> 00:50:56,380
we could measure modularity,

871
00:50:56,380 --> 00:50:57,380
coupling,

872
00:50:57,380 --> 00:50:58,380
cohesion,

873
00:50:58,380 --> 00:51:00,380
or structural complexity.

874
00:51:00,380 --> 00:51:04,079
For source code,

875
00:51:04,079 --> 00:51:10,130
we often measure lines of code,

876
00:51:10,130 --> 00:51:12,840
cinematic complexity,

877
00:51:12,840 --> 00:51:16,639
structuredness,

878
00:51:16,639 --> 00:51:22,389
or reuse level.

879
00:51:22,389 --> 00:51:24,389
For documentation,

880
00:51:24,389 --> 00:51:28,480
we might examine length,

881
00:51:28,480 --> 00:51:31,920
completeness,

882
00:51:31,920 --> 00:51:32,920
readability,

883
00:51:32,920 --> 00:51:34,920
or consistency.

884
00:51:34,920 --> 00:51:40,400
For test data,

885
00:51:40,400 --> 00:51:44,659
we might measure coverage,

886
00:51:44,659 --> 00:51:45,659
size,

887
00:51:45,659 --> 00:51:48,659
or fault detection capability.

888
00:51:48,659 --> 00:51:56,750
The key insight here is that

889
00:51:56,750 --> 00:52:00,750
software development is like a production line.

890
00:52:00,750 --> 00:52:07,360
Each stage produces artifacts

891
00:52:07,360 --> 00:52:17,239
that influence later stages.

892
00:52:17,239 --> 00:52:20,239
If requirements are ambitious,

893
00:52:20,239 --> 00:52:24,400
design quality may suffer.

894
00:52:24,400 --> 00:52:29,280
If design structure is weak,

895
00:52:29,280 --> 00:52:34,150
code reliability may decrease.

896
00:52:34,150 --> 00:52:35,309
So,

897
00:52:35,309 --> 00:52:40,110
product measurement gives us visibility

898
00:52:40,110 --> 00:52:45,110
into quality only in the lifecycle.

899
00:52:45,110 --> 00:52:48,039
Instead of waiting

900
00:52:48,039 --> 00:52:52,039
until deployments to detect problems,

901
00:52:52,039 --> 00:52:57,159
we analyze intermediate artifacts.

902
00:52:57,159 --> 00:53:03,079
Another important point is the difference

903
00:53:03,079 --> 00:53:09,400
between internal and external product attributes.

904
00:53:09,400 --> 00:53:15,250
Internal attributes describe structure,

905
00:53:15,250 --> 00:53:19,719
like size or complexity.

906
00:53:19,719 --> 00:53:23,719
External attributes describe behavior,

907
00:53:23,719 --> 00:53:27,719
like reliability or usability.

908
00:53:27,719 --> 00:53:34,320
Most early stage product measurements

909
00:53:34,320 --> 00:53:41,429
focus on internal attributes.

910
00:53:41,429 --> 00:53:42,429
Later,

911
00:53:42,429 --> 00:53:46,429
when the system runs in its environments,

912
00:53:46,429 --> 00:53:51,429
we evaluate external attributes.

913
00:53:51,429 --> 00:53:53,429
In summary,

914
00:53:53,429 --> 00:53:58,619
products exist throughout the lifecycle.

915
00:53:58,619 --> 00:54:03,130
A measurement must follow them

916
00:54:03,130 --> 00:54:05,130
at every stage,

917
00:54:05,130 --> 00:54:08,130
not only at delivery.

918
00:54:08,130 --> 00:54:38,639
Yes.

919
00:54:38,639 --> 00:54:41,639
Now we come to a very important idea

920
00:54:41,639 --> 00:54:43,639
in software measurements.

921
00:54:43,639 --> 00:54:45,059
The structural,

922
00:54:45,059 --> 00:54:50,780
the structural assumption.

923
00:54:50,780 --> 00:54:53,780
The structural assumption says that

