00:54:53,780 --> 00:54:56,780
good internal structure

925
00:54:56,780 --> 00:55:02,030
leads to good external quality.

926
00:55:02,030 --> 00:55:03,030
On the left side,

927
00:55:03,030 --> 00:55:05,030
we see internal structure.

928
00:55:05,030 --> 00:55:13,230
Things like modularity or low coupling

929
00:55:13,230 --> 00:55:17,159
and high cohesion.

930
00:55:17,159 --> 00:55:21,920
These are internal product attributes.

931
00:55:21,920 --> 00:55:22,920
They describe

932
00:55:22,920 --> 00:55:25,920
how the system is organized.

933
00:55:25,920 --> 00:55:33,199
How the system is organized internally.

934
00:55:33,199 --> 00:55:35,199
They describe

935
00:55:35,199 --> 00:55:39,199
how the system is organized internally.

936
00:55:39,199 --> 00:55:43,269
We can measure them without running the software.

937
00:55:43,269 --> 00:55:47,130
We can inspect diagrams.

938
00:55:47,130 --> 00:55:51,449
We can analyze code.

939
00:55:51,449 --> 00:55:54,599
On the right side,

940
00:55:54,599 --> 00:55:57,599
we see external quality.

941
00:55:57,599 --> 00:56:04,420
They are internal and external attributes,

942
00:56:04,420 --> 00:56:06,639
such as maintainability,

943
00:56:06,639 --> 00:56:08,639
reliability,

944
00:56:08,639 --> 00:56:12,400
or user satisfaction.

945
00:56:12,400 --> 00:56:17,760
These depend on behavioral in real use.

946
00:56:17,760 --> 00:56:20,760
They reflect how the system performs

947
00:56:20,760 --> 00:56:26,900
in its environments.

948
00:56:26,900 --> 00:56:28,900
Between these two sides,

949
00:56:28,900 --> 00:56:31,349
there is a bridge.

950
00:56:31,349 --> 00:56:33,349
And that bridge represents

951
00:56:33,349 --> 00:56:46,039
If the internal structure is strong, then external quality will also be strong.

952
00:56:49,869 --> 00:57:02,679
So, if the internal structure is strong, that means the external quality will also be strong.

953
00:57:02,679 --> 00:57:08,269
This idea has been widely accepted in software engineering.

954
00:57:09,659 --> 00:57:31,670
Frederick Brooks, in his book, My Tickle Month, emphasizes that good top-down design makes flaws more visible.

955
00:57:31,670 --> 00:57:38,190
Structural design methods.

956
00:57:39,409 --> 00:57:39,449
Objects.

957
00:57:40,389 --> 00:57:48,690
Object-oriented design and modern architectural principles are all built on this belief.

958
00:57:51,139 --> 00:58:03,269
If we give an example, high cohesion suggests models are focused and understandable.

959
00:58:05,010 --> 00:58:12,300
Low coupling suggests changes in one model will not heavily affect others.

960
00:58:12,440 --> 00:58:16,030
Clear structure suggests easier.

961
00:58:16,849 --> 00:58:27,380
testing and modification. All of these internal properties are expected to

962
00:58:27,380 --> 00:58:41,000
improve external outcomes like maintainability and reliability.

963
00:58:41,000 --> 00:58:57,159
However, this is still an assumption. It's intuitive but it must be

964
00:58:57,159 --> 00:59:05,840
validated. Just because a system works well-structured does not automatically

965
00:59:05,840 --> 00:59:14,750
guarantee high reliability or user satisfaction. This is where measurement

966
00:59:14,750 --> 00:59:24,690
becomes critical. Measurement allows us to test whether this bridge is strong. We

967
00:59:24,690 --> 00:59:31,710
can collect data on internal attributes and compare them

968
00:59:31,710 --> 00:59:39,849
with external outcomes. Over time we can determine whether strong structure

969
00:59:39,849 --> 00:59:50,500
truly correlates with high quality. So the key message here is this. We assume

970
00:59:50,500 --> 00:59:59,840
good structure leads to good quality. But only careful measurement can confirm

971
00:59:59,840 --> 01:00:37,480
that relationship.

972
01:00:37,579 --> 01:00:52,769
Now we have Slide 10. The danger of a single quality metric. Here we examine an

973
01:00:52,769 --> 01:01:02,860
important warning, danger of single quality metric. In many organizations

974
01:01:02,860 --> 01:01:16,650
there is a temptation to reduce quality to one number. A single index. A single

975
01:01:16,650 --> 01:01:17,949
score.

976
01:01:17,949 --> 01:01:26,170
Sometimes simple, that quickly reads and compares.

977
01:01:26,170 --> 01:01:29,230
But this approach is risky.

978
01:01:29,230 --> 01:01:35,980
The slide represents the GNP analogy.

979
01:01:35,980 --> 01:01:47,849
It means Gross National Product is a composite number that summarizes the economic output of a country.

980
01:01:47,849 --> 01:01:56,860
However, GNP is not the same as happiness.

981
01:01:56,860 --> 01:02:08,860
A country can have high economic output while still having social problems, inequality or low life satisfaction.

982
01:02:08,860 --> 01:02:30,139
Similarly, in software engineering, code complexity is not equal to quality.

983
01:02:30,139 --> 01:02:36,059
Complexity is an internal attribute.

984
01:02:36,059 --> 01:02:40,789
It measures structural characteristics of code.

985
01:02:40,789 --> 01:02:46,429
But quality is multidimensional.

986
01:02:46,429 --> 01:02:55,590
It includes reliability, maintainability, usability, performance and more.

987
01:02:55,590 --> 01:03:07,780
When we create a single quality index, we combine different internal attributes into one composite number.

988
01:03:07,780 --> 01:03:09,829
But,

989
01:03:09,829 --> 01:03:15,460
this creates several problems.

990
01:03:15,460 --> 01:03:21,460
The weights assigned to each component may be arbitrary.

991
01:03:21,460 --> 01:03:26,030
Important dimensions may be ignored.

992
01:03:26,030 --> 01:03:34,340
A high overall score may hide weaknesses in specific areas.

993
01:03:34,340 --> 01:03:44,170
For example, a simple may have low complexity but poor documentation.

994
01:03:44,170 --> 01:03:45,170
Or,

995
01:03:45,170 --> 01:03:49,170
a small may have strong modularity but low usability.

996
01:03:49,170 --> 01:03:54,869
A single metric can hide these differences.

997
01:03:54,869 --> 01:04:02,940
The image on the left side illustrates this idea.

998
01:04:02,940 --> 01:04:14,170
There is an internal rule filter rejecting a model simply because it contains many go-to statements.

999
01:04:14,170 --> 01:04:18,030
Counting go-tos

1000
01:04:18,030 --> 01:04:24,030
might be used as a crude structural indicator.

1001
01:04:24,030 --> 01:04:25,030
But,

1002
01:04:25,030 --> 01:04:33,099
eliminating a model based only on that rule does not guarantee better quality.

1003
01:04:33,099 --> 01:04:44,070
This highlights an important principle.

1004
01:04:44,070 --> 01:04:46,070
Internal metrics are useful.

1005
01:04:46,070 --> 01:04:47,070
But,

1006
01:04:47,070 --> 01:04:55,610
they are only partial indicators.

1007
01:04:55,610 --> 01:05:00,019
Composite measures must be validated carefully.

1008
01:05:00,019 --> 01:05:02,019
We must ask,

1009
01:05:02,019 --> 01:05:10,179
do the components fully represent what we mean by quality?

1010
01:05:10,179 --> 01:05:13,179
Are the weights justified?

1011
01:05:13,179 --> 01:05:23,099
Does the composite measure correlate with external attributes like reliability and user satisfaction?

1012
01:05:23,099 --> 01:05:27,539
Quality is multidimensional.

1013
01:05:27,539 --> 01:05:31,800
Reducing it to one number

1014
01:05:31,800 --> 01:05:36,800
can oversimplify reality.

1015
01:05:36,800 --> 01:05:40,920
So, the key measure here is caution.

1016
01:05:40,920 --> 01:05:47,590
Measurements should clarify reality but

1017
01:05:47,590 --> 01:05:53,659
not hide it behind a single convenient index.

1018
01:05:53,659 --> 01:06:13,440
Yes.

1019
01:06:13,440 --> 01:06:24,300
Now,

1020
01:06:24,300 --> 01:06:29,300
we come to the third measure entity in our framework.

1021
01:06:29,300 --> 01:06:31,780
Resources.

1022
01:06:31,780 --> 01:06:45,110
Resources are the inputs required for software production.

1023
01:06:45,110 --> 01:06:47,110
Without resources,

1024
01:06:47,110 --> 01:06:52,179
no process can operate and no product can be created.

1025
01:06:52,179 --> 01:06:54,940
In this slide,

1026
01:06:54,940 --> 01:07:01,170
resources are grouped into three main categories.

1027
01:07:01,170 --> 01:07:03,780
Personal,

1028
01:07:03,780 --> 01:07:05,780
Tools,

1029
01:07:05,780 --> 01:07:07,780
and Environments.

1030
01:07:07,780 --> 01:07:11,800
Now, let's begin with Personal.

1031
01:07:11,800 --> 01:07:16,250
Personal indicates developers,

1032
01:07:16,250 --> 01:07:19,250
testers or designers,

1033
01:07:19,250 --> 01:07:21,309
managers,

1034
01:07:21,309 --> 01:07:24,590
teams.

1035
01:07:24,590 --> 01:07:27,590
When measuring personal,

1036
01:07:27,590 --> 01:07:31,590
we often focus on attributes such as

1037
01:07:31,590 --> 01:07:34,139
experience,

1038
01:07:34,139 --> 01:07:35,139
for example,

1039
01:07:35,139 --> 01:07:39,900
number of years in software development,

1040
01:07:39,900 --> 01:07:41,900
or intelligence,

1041
01:07:41,900 --> 01:07:44,929
intelligence or skill level,

1042
01:07:44,929 --> 01:07:46,929
team size,

1043
01:07:46,929 --> 01:07:50,500
or communicates structure.

1044
01:07:50,500 --> 01:07:58,329
These attributes influence productivity and product quality.

1045
01:07:58,329 --> 01:07:59,329
For example,

1046
01:07:59,329 --> 01:08:06,329
a highly experienced team may produce more maintainable calls.

1047
01:08:06,329 --> 01:08:07,329
However,

1048
01:08:07,329 --> 01:08:16,260
simply increasing team size does not always increase productivity.

1049
01:08:16,260 --> 01:08:28,550
Measurement helps us understand these relationships.

1050
01:08:28,550 --> 01:08:33,149
Next, we look at Tools.

1051
01:08:33,149 --> 01:08:39,539
Tools include hardware and software systems used during development.

1052
01:08:39,539 --> 01:08:41,539
We might measure

1053
01:08:41,539 --> 01:08:44,600
software speed,

1054
01:08:44,600 --> 01:08:47,890
software license cost,

1055
01:08:47,890 --> 01:08:49,890
storage capacity,

1056
01:08:49,890 --> 01:08:58,350
and automation level.

1057
01:08:58,350 --> 01:09:02,350
Tool attributes affect process efficiency,

1058
01:09:02,350 --> 01:09:03,350
for example,

1059
01:09:03,350 --> 01:09:08,989
caster hardware may reduce build time.

1060
01:09:08,989 --> 01:09:13,989
Advanced testing tools may increase defect detection rates,

1061
01:09:13,989 --> 01:09:14,989
but

1062
01:09:14,989 --> 01:09:17,989
tools also introduce

1063
01:09:17,989 --> 01:09:19,989
cost,

1064
01:09:19,989 --> 01:09:27,020
so their benefits must justify their investments.

1065
01:09:27,020 --> 01:09:30,020
Finally, we consider the Environments.

1066
01:09:30,020 --> 01:09:32,020
Environments includes

1067
01:09:32,020 --> 01:09:33,109
physical

1068
01:09:33,109 --> 01:09:36,109
and organizational conditions,

1069
01:09:36,109 --> 01:09:37,180
such as

1070
01:09:37,180 --> 01:09:40,180
office space,

1071
01:09:40,180 --> 01:09:42,529
temperature,

1072
01:09:42,529 --> 01:09:43,529
lighting,

1073
01:09:43,529 --> 01:09:47,529
and workplace ergonomics.

1074
01:09:47,529 --> 01:09:58,359
These may seem secondary,

1075
01:09:58,359 --> 01:10:02,359
but they influence human performance.

1076
01:10:02,359 --> 01:10:10,060
A pure environment can reduce concentration and productivity.

1077
01:10:10,060 --> 01:10:13,659
Measurements make

1078
01:10:13,659 --> 01:10:19,420
these factors visible.

1079
01:10:19,420 --> 01:10:25,420
The slide emphasizes that resources are measured in three main dimensions.

1080
01:10:25,420 --> 01:10:28,829
Magnitude

1081
01:10:28,829 --> 01:10:31,409
how many,

1082
01:10:31,409 --> 01:10:32,409
for instance,

1083
01:10:32,409 --> 01:10:34,409
number of developers,

1084
01:10:34,409 --> 01:10:36,909
cost,

1085
01:10:36,909 --> 01:10:40,319
how much,

1086
01:10:40,319 --> 01:10:41,319
for instance,

1087
01:10:41,319 --> 01:10:45,319
to licensing expenses,

1088
01:10:45,319 --> 01:10:48,380
and quality,

1089
01:10:48,380 --> 01:10:50,380
what level of skill or capability.

1090
01:10:51,380 --> 01:10:58,000
An important concept here is Productivity.

1091
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:05,159
Productivity often combines product outputs with resource efforts.

1092
01:11:05,159 --> 01:11:07,989
For example,

1093
01:11:07,989 --> 01:11:09,989
output efforts

1094
01:11:09,989 --> 01:11:16,560
disconnects resources with processes and products.

1095
01:11:16,560 --> 01:11:20,750
So when analyzing project performance,

1096
01:11:20,750 --> 01:11:23,739
we must ask

1097
01:11:23,739 --> 01:11:25,739
are resource levels

1098
01:11:25,739 --> 01:11:28,739
appropriate

1099
01:11:28,739 --> 01:11:33,800
or it is in good level?

1100
01:11:33,800 --> 01:11:38,050
Is the skill level sufficient?

1101
01:11:38,050 --> 01:11:42,039
Are tools improving efficiency?

1102
01:11:42,039 --> 01:11:45,039
Is the environment supporting performance?

1103
01:11:45,039 --> 01:11:49,710
These are the questions we must ask

1104
01:11:49,710 --> 01:11:52,710
when analyzing project performance.

1105
01:11:52,710 --> 01:11:59,640
Measurement of resources allows managers to control inputs

1106
01:11:59,640 --> 01:12:06,710
in order to improve outputs.

1107
01:12:06,710 --> 01:12:09,899
With these slides,

1108
01:12:09,899 --> 01:12:13,899
we now complete the three entity model,

1109
01:12:13,899 --> 01:12:15,899
processes,

1110
01:12:15,899 --> 01:12:16,899
products,

1111
01:12:16,899 --> 01:12:18,899
and resources.

1112
01:12:18,899 --> 01:12:22,989
The full geometry also bear measurements.

1113
01:12:22,989 --> 01:12:27,270
We have completed here.

1114
01:12:27,270 --> 01:12:35,479
So let's take a look at what the next slide is.

1115
01:12:35,479 --> 01:12:37,479
The Productivity Equation.

1116
01:12:37,479 --> 01:12:45,270
Yes.

1117
01:12:45,270 --> 01:12:48,270
The Productivity Equation.

1118
01:12:48,270 --> 01:12:55,869
Now we examine one of the most fundamental concepts

1119
01:12:55,869 --> 01:12:59,539
in resource management.

1120
01:12:59,539 --> 01:13:03,659
The Productivity Equation.

1121
01:13:03,659 --> 01:13:06,500
The equation is simple.

1122
01:13:06,500 --> 01:13:09,500
Productivity equals to

1123
01:13:09,500 --> 01:13:11,500
amount of outputs,

1124
01:13:11,500 --> 01:13:12,500
division,

1125
01:13:12,500 --> 01:13:13,500
efforts,

1126
01:13:13,500 --> 01:13:16,000
inputs.

1127
01:13:16,000 --> 01:13:18,000
At first glance,

1128
01:13:18,000 --> 01:13:21,000
this looks straightforward.

1129
01:13:21,000 --> 01:13:25,670
If we produce more outputs

1130
01:13:25,670 --> 01:13:29,380
with less efforts,

1131
01:13:29,380 --> 01:13:33,239
productivity increases.

1132
01:13:33,239 --> 01:13:35,239
If effort increases

1133
01:13:35,239 --> 01:13:38,239
without increasing outputs,

1134
01:13:38,239 --> 01:13:48,819
productivity decreases.

1135
01:13:48,819 --> 01:13:50,819
But in software engineering,

1136
01:13:50,819 --> 01:13:56,590
this equation is more complex than it appears.

1137
01:13:56,590 --> 01:13:58,590
In manufacturing,

1138
01:13:58,590 --> 01:14:01,779
productivity is often linear.

1139
01:14:01,779 --> 01:14:07,899
A factory produces identical items repeatedly.

1140
01:14:07,899 --> 01:14:14,380
If you add more workers or fesser machines,

1141
01:14:14,380 --> 01:14:19,380
output increases in a predictable way.

1142
01:14:19,380 --> 01:14:21,800
This is replication.

1143
01:14:21,800 --> 01:14:28,949
The relationship between input and output is relatively stable.

1144
01:14:28,949 --> 01:14:33,989
Software development,

1145
01:14:33,989 --> 01:14:34,989
uh,

1146
01:14:34,989 --> 01:14:35,989
is different.

1147
01:14:35,989 --> 01:14:39,310
It's not replication.

1148
01:14:39,310 --> 01:14:42,310
It's design and creation.

1149
01:14:42,310 --> 01:14:44,380
Each system,

1150
01:14:44,380 --> 01:14:45,380
each future,

1151
01:14:45,380 --> 01:14:48,380
each model can be unique.

1152
01:14:48,380 --> 01:14:53,380
The relationship between effort and output is non-linear.

1153
01:14:53,380 --> 01:15:00,560
For example,

1154
01:15:00,560 --> 01:15:07,560
adding more developers does not always increase output proportionally.

1155
01:15:07,560 --> 01:15:09,140
Sometimes,

1156
01:15:09,140 --> 01:15:12,140
communication overheat increases.

1157
01:15:12,140 --> 01:15:15,140
Coordination becomes harder.

1158
01:15:15,140 --> 01:15:19,140
Productivity per person may decrease.

1159
01:15:19,140 --> 01:15:22,579
This is known in project management

1160
01:15:22,579 --> 01:15:27,579
as diminishing returns in team scaling.

1161
01:15:27,579 --> 01:15:32,479
Another important issue is defining output.

1162
01:15:32,479 --> 01:15:38,079
What counts as output in software?

1163
01:15:38,079 --> 01:15:42,770
Linus quotes

1164
01:15:42,770 --> 01:15:45,140
or

1165
01:15:45,140 --> 01:15:47,140
functionality delivered

1166
01:15:47,140 --> 01:15:51,199
or story points completed,

1167
01:15:51,199 --> 01:15:56,930
number of models implemented.

1168
01:15:56,930 --> 01:16:07,829
Different definitions of output lead to different productivity values.

1169
01:16:07,829 --> 01:16:14,859
Effort input is usually measured in person hours or person months.

1170
01:16:14,859 --> 01:16:19,859
But even effort measurements can vary depending on

1171
01:16:19,859 --> 01:16:23,250
whether we include rework,

1172
01:16:23,250 --> 01:16:25,279
testing,

1173
01:16:25,279 --> 01:16:28,340
or documentation.

1174
01:16:28,340 --> 01:16:33,340
This slide also highlights an important insight.

1175
01:16:33,340 --> 01:16:35,689
A productive worker

1176
01:16:35,689 --> 01:16:37,689
in one process

1177
01:16:37,689 --> 01:16:48,390
may become less productive if the process changes.

1178
01:16:48,390 --> 01:16:50,390
What does that mean?

1179
01:16:50,390 --> 01:16:52,390
This means

1180
01:16:52,390 --> 01:16:54,390
productivity depends

1181
01:16:54,390 --> 01:16:55,710
on,

1182
01:16:55,710 --> 01:16:58,710
depends not only on personal,

1183
01:16:58,710 --> 01:17:01,739
but also on process,

1184
01:17:01,739 --> 01:17:02,739
structure,

1185
01:17:02,739 --> 01:17:04,739
and tool support.

1186
01:17:04,739 --> 01:17:08,130
So while the productivity equation

1187
01:17:08,130 --> 01:17:12,829
works simply mathematically,

1188
01:17:12,829 --> 01:17:15,829
its interpretation in software engineering

1189
01:17:15,829 --> 01:17:19,829
requires careful definition

1190
01:17:19,829 --> 01:17:23,859
of both output and effort.

1191
01:17:23,859 --> 01:17:35,779
Productivity is not just about

1192
01:17:35,779 --> 01:17:38,300
working harder.

1193
01:17:38,300 --> 01:17:43,300
It's about organizing processes and resources effectively

1194
01:17:43,300 --> 01:18:03,689
to produce meaningful outputs.

1195
01:18:03,689 --> 01:18:08,750
Now we address a practical challenge in software measurements

1196
01:18:08,750 --> 01:18:10,750
using

1197
01:18:10,750 --> 01:18:13,750
surrogates for prediction.

1198
01:18:13,750 --> 01:18:21,020
This is a dilemma in software engineering.

1199
01:18:21,020 --> 01:18:23,020
Many of the attributes we care about

1200
01:18:23,020 --> 01:18:25,020
most,

1201
01:18:25,020 --> 01:18:27,020
such as cost,

1202
01:18:27,020 --> 01:18:28,020
reliability,

1203
01:18:28,020 --> 01:18:30,020
and user satisfaction,

1204
01:18:30,020 --> 01:18:33,340
are external attributes.

1205
01:18:33,340 --> 01:18:35,380
They depend on

1206
01:18:35,380 --> 01:18:37,380
real-world usage.

1207
01:18:37,380 --> 01:18:41,380
They often appear

1208
01:18:41,380 --> 01:18:44,859
late in the development lifecycle.

1209
01:18:44,859 --> 01:18:49,909
And they are difficult to measure early.

1210
01:18:49,909 --> 01:18:50,909
For example,

1211
01:18:50,909 --> 01:18:53,909
we cannot fully measure system reliability,

1212
01:18:53,909 --> 01:19:00,140
reliability before deployments.

1213
01:19:00,140 --> 01:19:04,390
We cannot precisely measure

1214
01:19:04,390 --> 01:19:06,390
long-term maintenance costs

1215
01:19:06,390 --> 01:19:10,840
before the system evolves.

1216
01:19:10,840 --> 01:19:16,930
But managers need estimates early.

1217
01:19:16,930 --> 01:19:18,930
Decisions must be made

1218
01:19:18,930 --> 01:19:21,930
before the final product exists.

1219
01:19:21,930 --> 01:19:25,439
So what is the strategy we use?

1220
01:19:25,439 --> 01:19:29,439
Internal attributes as surrogates.

1221
01:19:29,439 --> 01:19:35,550
A surrogate is a substitute indicator.

1222
01:19:35,550 --> 01:19:39,840
Instead of directly measuring reliability,

1223
01:19:39,840 --> 01:19:42,840
we measure something related to it,

1224
01:19:42,840 --> 01:19:50,770
such as design faults,

1225
01:19:50,770 --> 01:19:52,859
code defects,

1226
01:19:52,859 --> 01:19:54,859
structural complexity,

1227
01:19:54,859 --> 01:20:00,659
or inspection results.

1228
01:20:00,659 --> 01:20:02,659
For instance,

1229
01:20:02,659 --> 01:20:09,380
if we detect a high number of decision faults early,

1230
01:20:09,380 --> 01:20:14,409
this may predict lower future reliability.

1231
01:20:14,409 --> 01:20:16,409
If modularity is strong

1232
01:20:16,409 --> 01:20:19,409
and coupling is low,

1233
01:20:19,409 --> 01:20:24,590
this may suggest better maintainability.

1234
01:20:24,590 --> 01:20:28,550
The key idea is prediction.

1235
01:20:28,550 --> 01:20:32,579
Internal attributes are measurable early,

1236
01:20:32,579 --> 01:20:36,579
because they are structural and static.

1237
01:20:36,579 --> 01:20:45,670
External attributes are observable later,

1238
01:20:45,670 --> 01:20:51,890
because they are behavioral and dynamic.

1239
01:20:51,890 --> 01:20:59,359
Surrogates connect the present to the future.

1240
01:20:59,359 --> 01:21:00,359
However,

1241
01:21:00,359 --> 01:21:05,470
this approach depends on validation.

1242
01:21:05,470 --> 01:21:11,720
A surrogate must have a demonstrated relationship

1243
01:21:11,720 --> 01:21:15,489
between the external outcome.

1244
01:21:15,489 --> 01:21:17,489
If there is no

1245
01:21:17,489 --> 01:21:20,489
empirical evidence linking

1246
01:21:20,489 --> 01:21:23,489
internal design faults to measure failures,

1247
01:21:23,489 --> 01:21:36,670
then the surrogate is unreliable.

1248
01:21:36,670 --> 01:21:38,670
So when using surrogates,

1249
01:21:38,670 --> 01:21:40,670
we must ask,

1250
01:21:40,670 --> 01:21:44,670
does this internal metric correlate

1251
01:21:44,670 --> 01:21:49,670
with an external attribute we care about?

1252
01:21:49,670 --> 01:21:56,399
Is the relationship stable across projects?

1253
01:21:56,399 --> 01:21:58,500
Has it been validated?

1254
01:21:58,500 --> 01:22:00,500
Empirically?

1255
01:22:02,319 --> 01:22:05,319
Surrogates allow early estimation

1256
01:22:05,319 --> 01:22:10,310
or estimation of future outcomes

1257
01:22:10,310 --> 01:22:17,619
based on measurable internal metrics.

1258
01:22:17,619 --> 01:22:40,060
In summary,

1259
01:22:40,060 --> 01:22:42,060
surrogates help us make

1260
01:22:42,060 --> 01:22:44,130
informed predictions

1261
01:22:44,130 --> 01:22:48,579
before external results are visible.

1262
01:22:48,579 --> 01:23:03,880
Now we turn to an essential concept

1263
01:23:03,880 --> 01:23:06,880
in software measurements.

1264
01:23:06,880 --> 01:23:25,720
Measurement over time.

1265
01:23:25,720 --> 01:23:31,739
Software systems are not static.

1266
01:23:31,739 --> 01:23:34,600
They evolve.

1267
01:23:34,600 --> 01:23:36,600
New features are added.

1268
01:23:36,600 --> 01:23:38,600
Bugs are fixed.

1269
01:23:38,600 --> 01:23:40,600
Teams change.

1270
01:23:40,600 --> 01:23:41,600
Tools improve.

1271
01:23:41,600 --> 01:23:43,600
Because of this,

1272
01:23:43,600 --> 01:23:47,600
measurement cannot focus on a single snapshot.

1273
01:23:47,600 --> 01:23:51,050
We must absorb trends.

1274
01:23:51,050 --> 01:23:58,180
The graph on the slide shows

1275
01:23:58,180 --> 01:24:02,180
attribute values across multiple versions.

1276
01:24:02,180 --> 01:24:06,310
Version 1, version 2, and version 3.

1277
01:24:06,310 --> 01:24:10,630
The horizontal axis represents time.

1278
01:24:10,630 --> 01:24:14,300
The vertical axis represents

1279
01:24:14,300 --> 01:24:28,760
the value of an attribute.

1280
01:24:28,760 --> 01:24:31,760
Let's interpret the example trends.

1281
01:24:31,760 --> 01:24:38,159
The orange line on the slide you can see,

1282
01:24:38,159 --> 01:24:43,380
this line represents design decay.

1283
01:24:43,380 --> 01:24:48,569
The orange line represents the design decay.

1284
01:24:48,569 --> 01:24:53,199
Over time, the value increases.

1285
01:24:53,199 --> 01:24:55,199
This may indicate

1286
01:24:55,199 --> 01:24:58,199
growing structural complexity

1287
01:24:58,199 --> 01:25:01,199
or decreasing modularity.

1288
01:25:01,199 --> 01:25:06,409
Even if the system is functional,

1289
01:25:06,409 --> 01:25:09,539
internal structure might be

1290
01:25:09,539 --> 01:25:12,789
deteriorating.

1291
01:25:13,789 --> 01:25:30,539
The blue line represents reliability growth.

1292
01:25:30,539 --> 01:25:33,539
Reliability may improve gradually

1293
01:25:33,539 --> 01:25:35,539
as defects are fixed

1294
01:25:35,539 --> 01:25:38,539
and testing improves.

1295
01:25:38,539 --> 01:25:48,699
This is a positive trend.

1296
01:25:48,699 --> 01:25:51,779
The dashed line represents

1297
01:25:51,779 --> 01:25:53,779
personal turnover.

1298
01:25:53,779 --> 01:25:58,739
This line fluctuates.

1299
01:25:58,739 --> 01:26:02,260
It shows that human resources,

1300
01:26:02,260 --> 01:26:06,380
the human resource changes,

1301
01:26:06,380 --> 01:26:10,380
the human resource changes

1302
01:26:10,380 --> 01:26:14,380
can vary significantly over time,

1303
01:26:14,380 --> 01:26:19,609
influencing both processes and products.

1304
01:26:19,609 --> 01:26:26,819
The key message here is that

1305
01:26:26,819 --> 01:26:28,819
the trends

1306
01:26:28,819 --> 01:26:31,819
the direction and rate of change

1307
01:26:31,819 --> 01:26:34,819
is often more important

1308
01:26:34,819 --> 01:26:38,229
than the current value.

1309
01:26:38,229 --> 01:26:41,229
A system with moderate complexity

1310
01:26:41,229 --> 01:26:45,229
but repeatedly increasing design decay

1311
01:26:45,229 --> 01:26:47,229
is more concerning

1312
01:26:47,229 --> 01:26:50,229
than a system with slightly higher

1313
01:26:50,229 --> 01:27:00,729
but stable complexity.

1314
01:27:00,729 --> 01:27:06,539
Similarly,

1315
01:27:06,539 --> 01:27:09,539
a temporary drop in reliability

1316
01:27:09,539 --> 01:27:11,539
may be less critical

1317
01:27:11,539 --> 01:27:15,539
than a continuous downward trend.

1318
01:27:15,539 --> 01:27:22,119
Measurement over time allows us to

1319
01:27:22,119 --> 01:27:25,119
detect design decay early,

1320
01:27:25,119 --> 01:27:29,569
observe improvements in reliability,

1321
01:27:29,569 --> 01:27:36,100
identify instability in resources,

1322
01:27:36,100 --> 01:27:39,100
evaluate process changes.

1323
01:27:39,100 --> 01:27:40,550
For example,

1324
01:27:40,550 --> 01:27:43,550
if we introduce a new inspection process,

1325
01:27:43,550 --> 01:27:45,550
we should track defects

1326
01:27:45,550 --> 01:27:48,550
density over multiple versions

1327
01:27:48,550 --> 01:27:52,550
to see if the change is effective.

1328
01:27:52,550 --> 01:27:56,479
This slide reminds us

1329
01:27:56,479 --> 01:27:59,479
that software measurement is dynamic.

1330
01:27:59,479 --> 01:28:03,479
We are not just measuring attributes.

1331
01:28:03,479 --> 01:28:05,479
We are tracing.

1332
01:28:05,479 --> 01:28:07,479
We are tracking evolution.

1333
01:28:07,479 --> 01:28:10,340
In practice,

1334
01:28:10,340 --> 01:28:12,340
effective management depends on

1335
01:28:12,340 --> 01:28:16,020
measuring,

1336
01:28:16,020 --> 01:28:18,020
understanding trends,

1337
01:28:18,020 --> 01:28:22,020
not just isolated numbers.

1338
01:28:22,020 --> 01:28:30,640
And I think this is our last slide.

1339
01:28:30,770 --> 01:28:34,859
Now we arrive at the full picture,

1340
01:28:34,859 --> 01:28:38,859
the complete goal-based framework.

1341
01:28:38,859 --> 01:28:40,729
At this point,

1342
01:28:40,729 --> 01:28:43,729
we have discussed processes,

1343
01:28:43,729 --> 01:28:45,729
products and resources,

1344
01:28:45,729 --> 01:28:48,729
and we have distinguished

1345
01:28:48,729 --> 01:28:50,729
between internal attributes

1346
01:28:50,729 --> 01:28:53,729
and external attributes.

1347
01:28:53,729 --> 01:28:57,300
This slide combines everything

1348
01:28:57,300 --> 01:28:59,300
into one structured wheel.

1349
01:28:59,300 --> 01:29:02,100
On the left side,

1350
01:29:02,100 --> 01:29:05,100
we see the three entities,

1351
01:29:05,100 --> 01:29:07,229
personal,

1352
01:29:07,229 --> 01:29:08,229
excuse me,

1353
01:29:08,229 --> 01:29:10,229
processes,

1354
01:29:10,229 --> 01:29:12,229
products and resources.

1355
01:29:12,229 --> 01:29:14,710
Across the top,

1356
01:29:14,710 --> 01:29:17,710
we see two categories of attributes,

1357
01:29:17,710 --> 01:29:20,670
internal attributes

1358
01:29:20,670 --> 01:29:22,670
and external attributes.

1359
01:29:23,670 --> 01:29:27,579
Yes,

1360
01:29:27,579 --> 01:29:30,579
discrete and structural grids,

1361
01:29:30,579 --> 01:29:33,579
each entity can have both

1362
01:29:33,579 --> 01:29:36,579
internal and external attributes.

1363
01:29:36,579 --> 01:29:38,939
For example,

1364
01:29:38,939 --> 01:29:39,939
for processes,

1365
01:29:39,939 --> 01:29:41,939
internal attributes,

1366
01:29:41,939 --> 01:29:42,939
efforts,

1367
01:29:42,939 --> 01:29:45,100
cycle time,

1368
01:29:45,100 --> 01:29:47,100
external attributes,

1369
01:29:47,100 --> 01:29:49,100
adoption and efficiency.

1370
01:29:49,100 --> 01:29:51,100
But for products,

1371
01:29:51,100 --> 01:29:53,100
internal attributes,

1372
01:29:53,100 --> 01:29:54,100
defects,

1373
01:29:54,100 --> 01:29:56,100
complexity,

1374
01:29:56,100 --> 01:29:58,319
external attributes,

1375
01:29:58,319 --> 01:30:00,319
usability and satisfaction.

1376
01:30:00,319 --> 01:30:02,899
For resources,

1377
01:30:02,899 --> 01:30:04,899
internal attributes,

1378
01:30:04,899 --> 01:30:07,960
capacity utilization,

1379
01:30:07,960 --> 01:30:09,960
external attributes,

1380
01:30:09,960 --> 01:30:10,960
costs,

1381
01:30:10,960 --> 01:30:12,960
return on investment,

1382
01:30:12,960 --> 01:30:17,020
or ROI.

1383
01:30:17,020 --> 01:30:20,020
This framework shows that measurement

1384
01:30:20,020 --> 01:30:22,050
is multidimensional.

1385
01:30:22,050 --> 01:30:25,050
We are not measuring only products.

1386
01:30:25,050 --> 01:30:27,050
We are not measuring only

1387
01:30:27,050 --> 01:30:29,050
internal metrics.

1388
01:30:29,050 --> 01:30:32,050
We are analyzing entities across

1389
01:30:32,050 --> 01:30:36,050
structural and behavioral dimensions.

1390
01:30:36,050 --> 01:30:38,909
Now let's look at the paths

1391
01:30:38,909 --> 01:30:39,909
to measurements.

1392
01:30:39,909 --> 01:30:41,909
On the right side,

1393
01:30:41,909 --> 01:30:45,909
it defines a clear sequence.

1394
01:30:45,909 --> 01:30:48,909
It defines the goal.

1395
01:30:48,909 --> 01:30:52,909
What do we want to improve?

1396
01:30:52,909 --> 01:30:54,909
Reliability, productivity,

1397
01:30:54,909 --> 01:30:56,909
or maintainability?

1398
01:30:56,909 --> 01:31:02,810
Classification of the entity.

1399
01:31:02,810 --> 01:31:04,810
Are we focusing on process,

1400
01:31:04,810 --> 01:31:07,810
a product or resource,

1401
01:31:07,810 --> 01:31:11,380
and select attributes?

1402
01:31:11,380 --> 01:31:14,380
Are we measuring an internal

1403
01:31:14,380 --> 01:31:16,380
structural property or an

1404
01:31:16,380 --> 01:31:19,380
external behavioral outcome?

1405
01:31:19,380 --> 01:31:22,539
Only after these steps do we

1406
01:31:22,539 --> 01:31:25,539
select specific metrics.

1407
01:31:25,539 --> 01:31:28,899
This is the essence of a goal-based

1408
01:31:28,899 --> 01:31:29,899
framework.

1409
01:31:29,899 --> 01:31:32,899
Measurement begins with intention.

1410
01:31:32,899 --> 01:31:35,930
It's not random data collection.

1411
01:31:35,930 --> 01:31:41,279
It's structured, aligned, and purposeful.

1412
01:31:41,279 --> 01:31:43,279
By following this framework,

1413
01:31:43,279 --> 01:31:47,279
organizations can ensure that metrics

1414
01:31:47,279 --> 01:31:50,279
are relevant to strategic goals.

1415
01:31:50,279 --> 01:31:54,949
Measurements support decision-making.

1416
01:31:54,949 --> 01:31:57,949
Internal indicators are connected

1417
01:31:57,949 --> 01:31:59,949
to external outcomes.

1418
01:31:59,949 --> 01:32:02,949
These slides bring together

1419
01:32:02,949 --> 01:32:05,949
the geometry, classification,

1420
01:32:05,949 --> 01:32:09,949
lenses, surrogates, and time dimension

1421
01:32:09,949 --> 01:32:12,949
into one coherent model.

1422
01:32:12,949 --> 01:32:16,300
Yes.

1423
01:32:16,300 --> 01:32:19,300
And this completes the structure's

1424
01:32:19,300 --> 01:32:22,810
foundation of goal-based software measurements.

1425
01:32:22,810 --> 01:32:26,810
Okay, we are up this week.

1426
01:32:26,810 --> 01:32:29,810
Thank you for listening to me.

1427
01:32:29,810 --> 01:32:33,810
So let's meet next week.

1428
01:32:33,810 --> 01:32:35,810
Take care of yourself.

1429
01:32:35,810 --> 01:32:36,810
Bye.

